
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `hp-levels` baraye namayesh dadan sathe joher (ink) dar printer-haye HP estefade mishavad. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad ta az meghdare joher baghi mande dar cartridge-haye khod etela' peyda konid. Agar `hplip` roye system shoma nasb shode bashad, in dastoor kar mikonad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-h`  --> ℹ️ Namayesh rahnamaye dastoor (help) va gozine-ha.
    🔹 `--debug` --> 🐛 Namayesh etela'at debug baraye peyda kardane moshkelat.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ hp-levels

    🔹 Namayesh sathe joher baraye hameye printer-haye HP nasb shode.

    $ hp-levels --debug

    🔹 Namayesh etela'at debug baraye peyda kardane moshkelat momken.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ hp-levels

    🔹 Agar printer shoma sathe joher ra neshan nadahad, ehtemalan printer shoma hamahang nist ya `hplip` dorost nasb nashode ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `hp-levels` command is used to display the ink levels for HP printers.  This command allows you to see the remaining ink levels in your cartridges. It requires `hplip` to be installed on your system.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-h`  --> ℹ️ Display the help message and options.
    🔹 `--debug` --> 🐛 Display debug information for troubleshooting.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ hp-levels

    🔹 Display ink levels for all installed HP printers.

    $ hp-levels --debug

    🔹 Display debug information to help troubleshoot potential issues.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ hp-levels

    🔹 If your printer is not showing ink levels, it may not be compatible or `hplip` might not be installed correctly.

